      {
        "number": 4,
        "title": "Two kinds of people — natural and spiritual (2:14-15)",
        "range": "2:14-15",
        "excerpt": "But a natural man does not accept the things of the Spirit of God, for they are foolishness to him; and he cannot understand them, because they are spiritually appraised.",
        "body": "Verses 14-15 complete the chapter's argument with an anthropology. If revelation comes through the Spirit, then those without the Spirit lack the receptive faculty for what He reveals. Paul names them *psuchikos* — from *psuchē* (soul/life), denoting the person who operates only by natural human faculties unaided by the Spirit. The translation 'natural' is correct; modern English 'soulful' badly mistranslates the term. Jude 19 uses *psuchikos* the same way — the unregenerate divisive false teachers are described as *psuchikos*, not having the Spirit.\n\nThe *psuchikos* man's relation to spiritual realities is described in three steps. First, he does not *receive* (*dechetai*) them — actively refuses, will not welcome. Second, they are *moria* (foolishness) to him — the same word Paul applied to the cross at 1:18, 1:23. Third, he *cannot* understand them (*ou dunatai gnōnai*) — the inability is constitutional, not merely volitional. The reason: spiritual realities are *spiritually appraised* (*pneumatikōs anakrinetai*). They require the Spirit-given faculty for evaluation, and the *psuchikos* man lacks that faculty.\n\nThis is one of the New Testament's clearest statements of what the Reformed tradition has called total depravity — not that the unregenerate person is as bad as he could be, but that no part of him (including his cognitive faculty) is uncorrupted enough to perceive divine reality on its own terms. Calvin's exposition of this verse is searching: the natural man can debate theology, parse texts, even teach religion as an academic discipline — but he cannot *appraise* spiritual content because he lacks the Spirit-given organ for doing so. Edwards builds his whole theology of religious affections on this distinction: there is a *sense of the heart* given by the Spirit that the natural man cannot manufacture.\n\nVerse 15 then turns to the *pneumatikos* — the spiritual person, the Spirit-indwelt believer. He *appraises all things* (*anakrinei panta*). The verb *anakrinō* is judicial-investigative: to examine, sift, evaluate. The spiritual person has the discernment to evaluate spiritual realities the natural man cannot perceive. And he himself is *appraised by no one* — meaning no merely natural assessor has the standing to judge him. This is not a claim that Christians are above all criticism; it is a structural claim about epistemic standing. The blind cannot adjudicate the paintings of the sighted.\n\nThis verse has been pastorally abused — used to dismiss legitimate critique. Paul's actual point is narrower: when natural-faculty observers attempt to evaluate the spiritual realities Christians live by, they lack the competence to render a verdict. Other spiritual believers can and do appraise (and Paul himself does so throughout the letter). But the *psuchikos* judgment of spiritual content carries no weight. The Corinthian Christians, intimidated by the Sophistic culture's verdict on Paul's unimpressive preaching style, needed to hear this.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Psuchikos* (2:14) — natural, unregenerate; pejorative in Paul and Jude. *Moria* (foolishness) — same word as 1:18 of the cross's appearance to the perishing. *Ou dunatai* — 'is not able'; the inability is ontological. *Anakrinō* (2:14, 15 ×2) — to examine, evaluate, appraise; judicial vocabulary used here epistemically. *Pneumatikos* (spiritual) — Spirit-indwelt, Spirit-formed, contrasted with both *psuchikos* (ch. 2) and *sarkikos* (ch. 3)."
      },
      {
        "number": 5,
        "title": "The climactic claim — we have the mind of Christ (2:16)",
        "range": "2:16",
        "excerpt": "For who has known the mind of the Lord, that he will instruct Him? But we have the mind of Christ.",
        "body": "Paul closes the chapter with a quotation from Isaiah 40:13 LXX: *Who has known the mind of the Lord, that he should instruct Him?* In its Isaianic context the question is rhetorical and expects the answer 'no one' — Yahweh's counsel is unsearchable, and no human being has the standing to tutor God. Paul cites the question and then subverts its expected answer with one of the most audacious *de* statements in the New Testament: *but we have the mind of Christ*.\n\nThe statement is corporate (*hēmeis*) — the believing community, indwelt by the Spirit who searches the depths of God (2:10), shares in the very mind (*nous*) of the incarnate Lord. The shift from *kuriou* (the Lord, Yahweh, in the Isaiah citation) to *Christou* (Christ) is itself a Christological claim — Paul applies the Old Testament's reference to Yahweh's unsearchable mind to Christ's mind, which believers now possess. This is not a casual rhetorical flourish; it is a high Christology compressed into a single phrase.\n\nWhat does it mean to 'have the mind of Christ'? Not omniscience. Not infallibility in every judgment. Not direct mystical access bypassing Scripture. The claim is more careful: the believing community, through the indwelling Spirit, participates in Christ's own perspective on reality. We see (in part, imperfectly, growing) what Christ sees — the cross as wisdom, the rulers of this age as passing away, the things freely given by God as ours, the natural appraisal of spiritual things as foolishness. The mind of Christ is a perspective, granted by the Spirit, that orients the believer's evaluative framework.\n\nNotice the chapter's complete arc. It began with Paul's deliberately weak arrival — no wisdom, no eloquence, just the testimony of Christ crucified. It ends with the highest possible claim: *we have the mind of Christ*. The movement from 2:1 to 2:16 is the movement from natural inadequacy to Spirit-given participation in divine self-knowledge. The Corinthians wanted a sophist; Paul gave them something infinitely greater — communion, by the Spirit, in the very mind of the crucified Lord of glory.\n\nThis is also the setup for chapter 3. Having claimed that believers *have the mind of Christ*, Paul will immediately confront the Corinthians with the fact that they are not living as if they do — they are *sarkikos* (fleshly), unable to receive solid food, divided by jealousy and strife. The third anthropological category (alongside *psuchikos* and *pneumatikos*) is the Spirit-indwelt believer who behaves as if he were not. That gap — between possession and practice — drives the entire pastoral argument of the letter.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Nous Kuriou* (mind of the Lord, Isaiah 40:13 LXX) → *nous Christou* (mind of Christ) — the substitution itself is a Christological claim. *Sumbibazō* (instruct, 2:16) — to bring together, advise, teach; the rhetorical question in Isaiah denies any creature can tutor God. *Echomen* (we have, present indicative) — current possession, not future hope. The chapter closes not with aspiration but with a stated fact about every Spirit-indwelt believer."
      }
